Loading required package: patchwork

Below is my attempt to work out the causal assumptions of our experimental study:

  • Source Credibility is (potentially) affected by importance, order, and religion.
  • Religion is affected by age, SES, education, gender, and country
  • SES is affeted by country, education, and age
  • Education is affected by country, age, and being male
  • Importance of statement is a function of religion, memory and country-level factors
  • memory is affected by age, education, and (perhaps) presentation order.
  • The exposure of interest is “religion”
  • The outcome of interest is “source credibility”

We graph the assumed model like this:

I might have misunderstood the model.

Please free to play around with the code to make sure what it fits with your causal assumptions.

Which variables should we condition on to enable causal inference for Rel–> Source Credibility?

  1. It is important to close all backdoors between religion and source credibility.

  2. Equally important, we must not open any paths between religion and source credibility by inadvertantly including a collider confounder. This latter point is under appreciated, however see: (Rohrer 2018; McElreath 2020; Pearl 2019). Note that (Rohrer 2018) is very accessible.

Note that, conditional on the assumptions of our model, we should either {condition on age, country and education} or we should condition on {country, memory, order}.

Condider what happens if we include “ses”:

p2 p3 <-ggdag_collider(dg_1, text = FALSE, use_labels = “label” ) + theme_dag_blank() + labs(title = “Lurking Colliders”) p3 library(patchwork)

p1 + p2 + p3 + plot_annotation(title =“Causal graph for estimating the effect of religion on source credibility study,” subtitle = "“, tag_levels =”a")
